    {
      "content": "Application Patterns and Development Strategies for SQL Server in Azure Virtual Machines",
      "pos": [
        689,
        777
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Summary:",
      "pos": [
        782,
        790
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Determining which application pattern or patterns to use for your SQL Server based applications in Azure environment is an important design decision and it requires a solid understanding of how SQL Server and each infrastructure component of Azure work together.",
      "pos": [
        792,
        1054
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "With SQL Server in Azure Infrastructure Services, you can easily migrate, maintain, and monitor your existing SQL Server applications built-on Windows Server to virtual machines in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        1055,
        1242
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The goal of this article is to provide solution architects and developers a foundation for good application architecture and design, which they can follow when migrating existing applications to Azure as well as developing new applications in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        1244,
        1493
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For each application pattern, you will find an on-premises scenario, its respective cloud-enabled solution, and the related technical recommendations.",
      "pos": [
        1495,
        1645
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, the article discusses Azure specific development strategies so that you can design your applications correctly.",
      "pos": [
        1646,
        1770
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Due to the many possible application patterns, it’s recommended that architects and developers should choose the most appropriate pattern for their applications and users.",
      "pos": [
        1771,
        1942
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        1944,
        2028
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Technical Contributors:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Luis Carlos Vargas Herring, Madhan Arumugam Ramakrishnan"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2030,
        2200
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Technical Reviewers:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Corey Sanders, Drew McDaniel, Narayan Annamalai, Nir Mashkowski, Sanjay Mishra, Silvano Coriani, Stefan Schackow, Tim Hickey, Tim Wieman, Xin Jin"
    },
    {
      "content": "Introduction",
      "pos": [
        2205,
        2217
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can develop many types of n-tier applications by separating the components of the different application layers on different machines as well as in separate components.",
      "pos": [
        2219,
        2390
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you can place the client application and business rules components in one machine, front-end web tier and data access tier components in another machine, and a back-end database tier in another machine.",
      "pos": [
        2391,
        2606
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This kind of structuring helps isolate each tier from each other.",
      "pos": [
        2607,
        2672
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you change where data comes from, you don’t need to change the client or web application but only the data access tier components.",
      "pos": [
        2673,
        2806
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        2808,
        2908
      ],
      "content": "A typical <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>n-tier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> application includes the presentation tier, the business tier, and the data tier:"
    },
    {
      "content": "Tier",
      "pos": [
        2913,
        2917
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Description",
      "pos": [
        2933,
        2944
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Presentation",
      "pos": [
        3315,
        3327
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3332,
        3440
      ],
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>presentation tier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> (web tier, front-end tier) is the layer in which users interact with an application."
    },
    {
      "content": "Business",
      "pos": [
        3516,
        3524
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3533,
        3710
      ],
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>business tier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> (middle tier) is the layer that the presentation tier and the data tier use to communicate with each other and includes the core functionality of the system."
    },
    {
      "content": "Data",
      "pos": [
        3717,
        3721
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        3734,
        3851
      ],
      "content": "The <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>data tier<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> is basically the server that stores an application's data (for example, a server running SQL Server)."
    },
    {
      "content": "Application layers describe the logical groupings of the functionality and components in an application; whereas tiers describe the physical distribution of the functionality and components on separate physical servers, computers, networks, or remote locations.",
      "pos": [
        3915,
        4176
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The layers of an application may reside on the same physical computer (the same tier) or may be distributed over separate computers (n-tier), and the components in each layer communicate with components in other layers through well-defined interfaces.",
      "pos": [
        4177,
        4428
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can think of the term tier as referring to physical distribution patterns such as two-tier, three-tier, and n-tier.",
      "pos": [
        4429,
        4548
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>2-tier application pattern<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> contains two application tiers: application server and database server.",
      "pos": [
        4549,
        4653
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The direct communication happens between the application server and the database server.",
      "pos": [
        4654,
        4742
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The application server contains both web-tier and business-tier components.",
      "pos": [
        4743,
        4818
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>3-tier application pattern<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, there are three application tiers: web server, application server, which contains the business logic tier and/or business tier data access components, and the database server.",
      "pos": [
        4819,
        5029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The communication between the web server and the database server happens over the application server.",
      "pos": [
        5030,
        5131
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For detailed information on application layers and tiers, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Application Architecture Guide<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/ff650706.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5132,
        5287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before you start reading this article, you should have knowledge on the fundamental concepts of SQL Server and Azure.",
      "pos": [
        5289,
        5406
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>SQL Server Books Online<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/bb545450.aspx)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>SQL Server in Azure Virtual Machines<ept id=\"p2\">](virtual-machines-sql-server-infrastructure-services.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Azure.com<ept id=\"p3\">](http://azure.microsoft.com)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5407,
        5644
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This article describes several application patterns that can be suitable for your simple applications as well as the highly complex enterprise applications.",
      "pos": [
        5646,
        5802
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Before detailing each pattern, we recommend that you should familiarize yourself with the available data storage services in Azure, such as <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure Storage<ept id=\"p1\">](../storage/storage-introduction.md)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Azure SQL Database<ept id=\"p2\">](../sql-database/sql-database-technical-overview.md)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>SQL Server in an Azure Virtual Machine<ept id=\"p3\">](virtual-machines-sql-server-infrastructure-services.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5803,
        6171
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To make the best design decisions for your applications, understand when to use which data storage service clearly.",
      "pos": [
        6172,
        6287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Choose SQL Server in an Azure Virtual Machine, when:",
      "pos": [
        6293,
        6345
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need control on SQL Server and Windows.",
      "pos": [
        6349,
        6392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, this might include the SQL Server version, special hotfixes, performance configuration, etc.",
      "pos": [
        6393,
        6498
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need a full compatibility with SQL Server on-premises and want to move existing applications to Azure as-is.",
      "pos": [
        6502,
        6614
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You want to leverage the capabilities of the Azure environment but Azure SQL Database does not support all the features that your application requires.",
      "pos": [
        6618,
        6769
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This could include the following areas:",
      "pos": [
        6770,
        6809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Database size<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: At the time this article was updated, SQL Database supports a database of up to 500 GB of data.",
      "pos": [
        6817,
        6931
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If your application requires more than 500 GB of data and you don’t want to implement custom sharding solutions, it’s recommended that you use SQL Server in an Azure Virtual Machine.",
      "pos": [
        6932,
        7114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For the latest information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Scaling Out Azure SQL Databases<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn495641.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Azure SQL Database Service Tiers and Performance Levels<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/dn741336.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7115,
        7355
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HIPAA compliance<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: Healthcare customers and Independent Software Vendors (ISVs) might choose <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>SQL Server in Azure Virtual Machines<ept id=\"p2\">](virtual-machines-sql-server-infrastructure-services.md)</ept> instead of <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Azure SQL Database<ept id=\"p3\">](../sql-database/sql-database-technical-overview.md)</ept> because SQL Server in an Azure Virtual Machine is covered by HIPAA Business Associate Agreement (BAA).",
      "pos": [
        7362,
        7739
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For information on compliance, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Azure Trust Center: Compliance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/support/trust-center/compliance/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7740,
        7879
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Instance-level features<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: At this time, SQL Database doesn’t support features that live outside of the database (such as Linked Servers, Agent jobs, FileStream, Service Broker, etc).",
      "pos": [
        7886,
        8071
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure SQL Database Guidelines and Limitations<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/ff394102.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        8072,
